You&#x27;ve misinterpreted, it&#x27;s not a question about reducing the annotation in a struct/enum definition, but about postponing the destruction of the String so that the later references are valid, i.e. currently we have<p><pre><code>  fn test_parse_unsafe() {
      let v = {
          let text = &quot;The cat&quot;.to_string();
          tokenize_string3(text.as_slice())
      }; // `text` destroyed here
      assert_eq!(vec![Word(&quot;The&quot;), Other(&quot; &quot;), Word(&quot;cat&quot;)], v);
  }
</code></pre>
but the suggestion/question is about changing this to<p><pre><code>  fn test_parse_unsafe() {
      let v = {
          let text = &quot;The cat&quot;.to_string();
          tokenize_string3(text.as_slice())
      }; 
      assert_eq!(vec![Word(&quot;The&quot;), Other(&quot; &quot;), Word(&quot;cat&quot;)], v);
  } // `text` destroyed here
</code></pre>
so that the references in `v` are valid.<p>This could lead to &quot;memory leaks&quot;, where a destructor is implicitly postponed to a higher scope, but I don&#x27;t think it would be much of a problem in practice (the promotion would only be through simple scopes, not through loops, and maybe not through `if`s). In fact, there&#x27;s an yet-to-be-implemented accepted RFC covering this[1] (there&#x27;s no guarantee that it will be implemented though, just that the idea is mostly sound).<p>[1]: <a href="https://github.com/rust-lang/rfcs/blob/master/active/0031-better-temporary-lifetimes.md" rel="nofollow">https://github.com/rust-lang/rfcs/blob/master/active/0031-be...</a>
